1
00:00:11,932 --> 00:00:14,588
So, let us assume that
the measuring of you

2
00:00:14,621 --> 00:00:16,786
and your proposal are done...

3
00:00:16,845 --> 00:00:18,429
and that we are partners...

4
00:00:18,470 --> 00:00:22,429
in a venture to acquire
and reform Nassau.

5
00:00:22,512 --> 00:00:23,971
Jack went to hunt Captain Flint.

6
00:00:24,054 --> 00:00:25,940
Chances are good you've
seen the last of him.

7
00:00:25,965 --> 00:00:28,388
When Anne was recruiting
spies in Port Royal,

8
00:00:28,429 --> 00:00:30,698
she met a man with an
estate in the wilderness.

9
00:00:30,723 --> 00:00:34,971
This man found it profitable to
offer his services to wealthy families

10
00:00:34,996 --> 00:00:37,829
with a need to make troublesome
family members disappear.

11
00:00:38,137 --> 00:00:39,804
What families?

12
00:00:39,887 --> 00:00:41,762
Flint doesn't need to get far.

13
00:00:41,787 --> 00:00:45,088
All he needs is to bury that gold
somewhere unknown and he's won.

14
00:00:45,113 --> 00:00:48,182
Accept the treaty and John Silver lives.

15
00:00:48,207 --> 00:00:51,498
This war, it will not be
bargained away to avoid a fight.

16
00:00:51,523 --> 00:00:52,742
Even if you could kill me,

17
00:00:52,767 --> 00:00:54,263
how are you going to explain it to her?

18
00:00:54,288 --> 00:00:55,654
She believes in this.

19
00:00:55,679 --> 00:00:58,651
If it costs a war to save her,
you'll have lost her anyway.

20
00:00:58,683 --> 00:01:01,934
Even you cannot construct a story
to make her forgive you that.

21
00:01:02,017 --> 00:01:05,226
Is this war more
important than her life?

22
00:01:07,618 --> 00:01:09,743
Answer the question.

23
00:01:10,106 --> 00:01:12,110
I wanna hear you say it.

24
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:21,653
What's to be done
with the unwanted ones?

25
00:01:23,270 --> 00:01:25,663
The men who do not fit,

26
00:01:26,027 --> 00:01:29,569
whom civilization must
prune from the vine

27
00:01:29,652 --> 00:01:32,804
to protect its sense of itself.

28
00:01:32,944 --> 00:01:36,944
Every culture since earliest
antiquity has survived this way,

29
00:01:37,019 --> 00:01:41,030
defining itself by
the things it excludes.

30
00:01:41,569 --> 00:01:43,986
So long as there is progress,

31
00:01:44,069 --> 00:01:46,654
there will always be
human debris in its wake,

32
00:01:46,679 --> 00:01:49,318
on the outside looking in.

33
00:01:49,757 --> 00:01:51,669
And sooner or later,

34
00:01:51,694 --> 00:01:54,986
one must answer the question...

35
00:01:55,069 --> 00:01:57,671
what becomes of them?

36
00:01:58,968 --> 00:02:00,466
In London,

37
00:02:00,491 --> 00:02:03,318
the solution is to call them criminals.

38
00:02:03,319 --> 00:02:06,111
To throw them in a deep, dark hole

39
00:02:06,136 --> 00:02:08,344
and hope it never runs over.

40
00:02:12,043 --> 00:02:16,111
I would argue that justice
demands we do better than that.

41
00:02:16,194 --> 00:02:20,715
That a civilization is
judged not by who it excludes,

42
00:02:20,788 --> 00:02:24,455
but by how it treats the excluded.

43
00:02:27,236 --> 00:02:29,819
That is not what I asked.

44
00:02:39,715 --> 00:02:43,569
Many of the men incarcerated
here have enemies, sir.

45
00:02:44,028 --> 00:02:47,278
Such is the nature of being
anathema to the empire.

46
00:02:47,497 --> 00:02:49,278
And the only way I can protect them

47
00:02:49,319 --> 00:02:51,944
is to ensure that once they
walk through these gates,

48
00:02:52,027 --> 00:02:55,318
their anonymity is protected, too.

49
00:02:55,637 --> 00:02:59,319
Here, they must cease to
be... to be able to find peace.

50
00:02:59,360 --> 00:03:03,944
I already said I'm not an enemy
of his, nor is the man who sent me.

51
00:03:04,027 --> 00:03:06,310
Yes, and I believe you when
you say it. But still...

52
00:03:06,335 --> 00:03:07,926
Do you know where I come from, sir?

53
00:03:07,986 --> 00:03:11,069
- No, I don't.
- I come from Nassau.

54
00:03:16,904 --> 00:03:20,404
My name is Tom Morgan.

55
00:03:23,152 --> 00:03:26,569
I come on behalf of Long John Silver.

56
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:32,910
Have you heard of him?

57
00:03:34,319 --> 00:03:35,949
Yes, of course.

58
00:03:37,506 --> 00:03:39,006
Good.

59
00:03:40,504 --> 00:03:44,715
Then I ask you again
and for the last time,

60
00:03:44,986 --> 00:03:48,004
is the prisoner we
are looking for here...

61
00:03:48,029 --> 00:03:49,913
or isn't he?

62
